      "role": "user",
      "content": "thanks, that looks mostly right. \n\nbut wait, i just realized something. what if the function returns something that isn't \"hashable\"? like if i have a test that returns a list or a dictionary? `set(results)` might throw a TypeError if the outputs are lists. \n\ncould you update it so it's more robust? i don't want the detector itself to crash if the test function returns complex data. just make sure it still follows the same logic (True if values change, False if they stay the same).\n\nhere is a quick test case for that:\n\n```python\ndef flaky_list_test():\n    return [1] if random.random() > 0.5 else [2]\n\ndef stable_list_test():\n    return [1]\n\n# Should still work and not crash\nassert detect_flakiness(flaky_list_test, n_runs=10) == True\nassert detect_flakiness(stable_list_test, n_runs=10) == False\n```",
